      <prompt>
        <p>A 60-year-old woman has a routine pre-operative ECG which shows flattened T waves, prolonged QT interval and U waves.</p>
        <p>Which is the most likely of the following?</p>
      </prompt>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_000">Acute myocardial infarction</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_001">Hyperkalaemia</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_002">Hypernatraemia</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_003">Hypokalaemia</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_004">Hypothermia</simpleChoice>
    </choiceInteraction>
  </itemBody>
  <modalFeedback identifier="CORRECT_FEEDBACK" outcomeIdentifier="GENERAL_FEEDBACK" showHide="show">
    <p>
      <b>Option D is Correct.</b>
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Option A is Incorrect.</b>
      This typically causes ST elevation, T wave inversion and Q waves.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Option B is Incorrect.</b>
      This typically causes tall tented T waves, widened QRS complex and small P waves.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Option C is Incorrect.</b>
      This does not usually causes ECG changes.
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>Option E is Incorrect.</b>
      The ECG may show J waves.
    </p>
  </modalFeedback>
